RENIN is the rate limiting enzyme in RAAS. It converts angiotensinogen from the liver to angiotensin I. ACE in the pulmonay epithelium converts angiotensin I to angiotensin II.

Adrenal insufficiency

Symptoms of adrenal insufficiency

Example: Addisonian crisis :
Deficient mineralocorticoids : (mineralocorticoid production may be preserved in some causes of adrenal dysfunction)
Deficient aldosterone -> decreased Na/K ATPase and ENaC -> Salt and water loss -> hypovolemia with shock,
Deficient glucocorticoids : hypoglycaemia

Compensatory rise in ACTH -> Hyperpigmentation

One presentation is acute adrenal insufficiency

  • This is rare in secondary or tertiary causes of adrenal insufficiency. (except pituitary apoplexy)
  • predominant symptom is shock + constiturional symptoms - fatigue, lethargy, N/V, abdominal pain.

Other presentation is chronic adrenal insufficiency

Patients with chronic primary adrenal insufficiency -> symptoms and signs of (1) glucocorticoid, (2)mineralocorticoid, and, in women, (3)androgen deficiency.
In contrast, patients with secondary or tertiary adrenal insufficiency usually have normal mineralocorticoid function.

+ Primary chronic adrenal insufficiency - weakness, malaise, anorexia, weight loss
+ Secondary or tertiary chronic adrenal insufficiency :

Koebner phenomenon

Other diseases showing koebner phenomenon

  • verruca vulgaris
  • [[#Lichen planus]]
  • vitiligo
  • psoriasis

LP, vitiligo and psoriasis show "true" koebner phenomenon while molluscum contagiosum and verruca vulgaris show pseudo-koebnerization. - https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553108/

Slowly (and spontaneously) resolving T cell mediated autoimmune disease

Wickhams striae: white lace - like patterns on the surface of lesions. - but not seen in all patients. Seen in most patients.
Affects skin, mucous membranes (especially the oral mucosa), scalp, nails, and genitalia - see UpToDate images
Unknown - possible autoimmune based involving CD 8 T cells

  • Vacuolization of the basal layer
  • Civatte bodies (apoptotic keratinocytes) in the lower epidermis
  • Wedge-shaped hypergranulosis, "saw-tooth" shaped rete ridges
  • Small clefts at the dermal-epidermal junction (Max-Joseph spaces)
  • Band-like, lymphocytic infiltrate at the dermal-epidermal junction
  • Eosinophilic, colloid bodies (apoptotic keratinocytes) in the papillary dermis
  • Pigment incontinence (most prominent in dark-skinned individuals)
    Cutaneous lichen planus usually resolves within 2 years.

ARNI - Antiotensin receptor- Neprilysin inhibitor drugs


Neprilysin degrades some peptides helpful in heart failure (like ANP etc) and also degrades angiotensin II (which is harmful).
So we give a neprilysin inhibitor together with an angiotensin receptor blocker to minimize the effects of the accuulated angiotensin.
An ACE inhibitor cannot be used instead of the ARB because ACEi and Neprilysin inhibitors both neprilysin inhibitors and ACE inhibitors increase bradykinin which can cause angioedema.

ACE degrades bradykinin -> inhibition of ACE -> accumulation of bradykinin -> Cough. (and angiooedema)

ARNI is beneficial in Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction.
